praecipua. Cic. preferred praepositus or praecipuus to productus as a transla- tion of προηγμένος (Finn. iv 26, 72). Chrysippus and his school classed these bodily advantages under the head of ἀδιάφορα κατ’ εἶδος προηγμέναε Posi- donius καὶ ταῦτά φησι τῶν ἀγαθῶν εἶναι

(Diog. L. vii 103): Cicero's language here, however, cannot be taken as prov- ing his indebtedness to Posidonius or even sympathy with his views. He merely says, as Chrysippus might have said, that health and strength of body were to tlze body what sanitas and con- sistency were to the mind. The difference between Chrysippus and Posidonius turned on the value to be assigned to physica] qualities in relation to the mind.
